09484nam a22014175i 9780823285594DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232855947 a10.1515/97808232855942doi  a(DE-B1597)555460  a(OCoLC)1117645098  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aCB351b.W47 2019eb 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a909.0722300aWhose Middle Ages? :bTeachable Moments for an Ill-Used Past /ced. by Andrew Albin, Mary C. Erler, Thomas O'Donnell, Nicholas L. Paul, Nina Rowe. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b35  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFordham Series in Medieval Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I – Stories -- tIntroduction -- tThe Invisible Peasantry -- tThe Hidden Narratives of Medieval Art -- tModern Intolerance and the Medieval Crusades -- tBlood Libel, a Lie and Its Legacies -- tWho’s Afraid of Shari‘a Law? -- tHow Do We Find Out About Immigrants in Later Medieval England? -- tThe Middle Ages in the Harlem Renaissance -- tPart II – Origins -- tIntroduction -- tThree Ways of Misreading Thomas Jefferson’s Qur’an -- tThe Nazi Middle Ages -- tWhat Would Benedict Do? -- tNo, People in the Middle East Haven’t Been Fighting Since the Beginning of Time -- tIvory and the Ties That Bind -- tBlackness, Whiteness, and the Idea of Race in Medieval European Art -- tEngland Between Empire and Nation in “The Battle of Brunanburh” -- tWhose Spain Is It, Anyway? -- tPart III – #Hashtags -- tIntroduction -- tModern Knights, Medieval Snails, and Naughty Nuns -- tCharting Sexuality and Stopping Sin -- t“Celtic” Crosses and the Myth of Whiteness -- tWhitewashing the “Real” Middle Ages in Popular Media -- tReal Men of the Viking Age -- t#DeusVult -- tOwn Your Heresy -- tAfterword: Medievalists and the Education of Desire -- tAppendixes -- tAppendix I: Possibilities for Teaching—By Genre -- tAppendix II: Possibilities for Teaching— by Course Theme -- tList of Contributors -- tAbout the Editors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhose Middle Ages? is an interdisciplinary collection of short, accessible essays intended for the nonspecialist reader and ideal for teaching at an undergraduate level. Each of twenty-two essays takes up an area where digging for meaning in the medieval past has brought something distorted back into the present: in our popular entertainment; in our news, our politics, and our propaganda; and in subtler ways that inform how we think about our histories, our countries, and ourselves. Each author looks to a history that has refused to remain past and uses the tools of the academy to read and re-read familiar stories, objects, symbols, and myths.Whose Middle Ages? gives nonspecialists access to the richness of our historical knowledge while debunking damaging misconceptions about the medieval past. Myths about the medieval period are especially beloved among the globally resurgent far right, from crusading emblems on the shields borne by alt-right demonstrators to the on-screen image of a purely white European populace defended from actors of color by Internet trolls. This collection attacks these myths directly by insisting that readers encounter the relics of the Middle Ages on their own terms.Each essay uses its author’s academic research as a point of entry and takes care to explain how the author knows what she or he knows and what kinds of tools, bodies of evidence, and theoretical lenses allow scholars to write with certainty about elements of the past to a level of detail that might seem unattainable. By demystifying the methods of scholarly inquiry, Whose Middle Ages? serves as an antidote not only to the far right’s errors of fact and interpretation but also to its assault on scholarship and expertise as valid means for the acquisition of knowledge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCivilization, MedievalxInfluence. 0aCivilization, Medieval. 0aMiddle Ages. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEurope.  aalt-right.  acrusades.  aglobalism.  amedievalism.  amiddle ages.  anation-state.  arace.  awhite supremacy.1 aAlbin, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBardsley, Sandy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBardsley, Sandy.1 aBishop, Adam M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBishop, Adam.1 aBleeke, Marian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBleeke, Marian.1 aCerbone, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCerbone, Will.1 aDiebold, William J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiebold, William.1 aDonner, Fred M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonner, Fred.1 aErler, Mary C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuérin, Sarah M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuérin, Sarah.1 aHeng, Geraldine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeng, Geraldine.1 aHornbeck, J. Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aII, J. Patrick Hornbeck.1 aMancia, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMancia, Lauren.1 aMulder, Stephennie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMulder, Stephennie.1 aO'Donnell, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOrmrod, W. Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrmrod, W. Mark.1 aPatto